We compare the results of the ICDTA4FL-ID3 model against the state-of-the-art, the Federated-ID3 model [8]. We present two tables, Tables 2 and 3, in which we show the results of the ICDTA4FL-ID3 model compared with the state-of-the-art for the datasets presented in Section 4.1. Table 2 presents the results when there is an IID data distribution, while Table 3 presents the results when there is a non-IID data distribution. The baseline model presents the mean result of the local DTs evaluated on its associated client.

references: We analyze the performance of the global model versus the local models by analyzing the class they predict and their associated rules. Table 6 presents three instances of the Nursery dataset that have been poorly classified by the local model and well classified by the global model. The first instance becomes well classified since the global model includes a condition on a characteristic (x5subscript𝑥5x_{5}) into the antecedent of the decision rule. The second instance becomes well classified since the global model replaces a condition of a characteristic (x3subscript𝑥3x_{3}) with a condition of another characteristic (x4subscript𝑥4x_{4}). The third instance becomes well classified by the global model, even having associated the same rule decision that the local model because it better defines the decision boundaries.
